description.narrative:
Limited participation by local business and citizen in the energy industry value chain due to the following barriers: (i) inadequate capacity of local suppliers to compete with foreign suppliers; (ii) lack of access by local suppliers to business opportunities available in the energy industry in Barbados; (iii) existing local content policies and regulatory requirements not being capable of effective implementation (by oversight authorities and International Companies); and (iv) the high capital and specialized inputs requirements for participation in the energy industry value chain.

The following intervention pathways are pursued under the project and targeted to reduce these four key barriers, culminating to progressively improving local supply: initiatives to enhance competitiveness and access to opportunities covering seminars for local manufacturers and service providers;  

The intervention pathways to addressing these barriers aim at increasing local supply by at least 11% - 15% of the value of the requirements for goods and services, as well as 50% of human resources requirements for International Companies operating in the energy sector in Barbados, over the first five years of this project implementation. The Commonwealth Secretariat’s technical assistance will lead to improved oversight by authorities and compliance by ICs to local content policies and regulations in Barbados.
